  "prompt": "Why is carbon monoxide dangerous?",
  "response": "Carbon monoxide (CO) is dangerous for several key reasons:\n\n1. Invisible and odorless\n- Cannot be detected by human senses\n- People can be exposed without knowing\n\n2. Interferes with oxygen transport\n- Binds to hemoglobin in blood much more strongly than oxygen\n- Prevents red blood cells from carrying oxygen to body tissues\n\n3. Toxic effects\n- Can cause oxygen deprivation in vital organs like brain and heart\n- Leads to symptoms like headache, dizziness, weakness, and nausea\n- High concentrations can cause unconsciousness and death\n\n4. Rapid accumulation\n- Can build up quickly in enclosed spaces\n- Common sources include faulty fuel-burning appliances, car exhaust, and incomplete combustion\n\n5. No immediate warning signs\n- Symptoms develop gradually\n- People may become disoriented before recognizing the danger\n\nDue to these characteristics, carbon monoxide is often called the \"silent killer\" and requires special detection equipment like CO alarms to warn of its presence.",
